{"about": "I am a Neuroscience major and Psychology minor at Georgia Tech who's interested in modulating the functional connectivity of neurological disorders, which may lead to improved interventions and cures in cognition. 

Besides my technical skills and ethical certifications, I bring intuition, dedication, and a high capacity for learning to my environments as I help those around me think through methods of data analysis, create new experimental stimuli, and ultimately drive a team to their final goals.", "educations": [{"school": "Georgia Institute of Technology", "degree": "Bachelor of Science - BS", "major": "Neuroscience", "start_date": "Aug 2022", "end_date": "Dec 2025", "description": "Grade: 3.71/4.00"}, {"school": "Grimsley High School", "degree": "International Baccalaureate Diploma", "major": null, "start_date": "2019", "end_date": "2022", "description": "Grade: 4.6974/5.00"}], "experiences": [{"title": "Georgia Tech Undergraduate Research Assistant", "company": "Cognitive Neuroscience at Tech Research Lab", "work_type": "Part-time", "start_date": "Aug 2022", "end_date": "Present", "location": "Atlanta, Georgia, United States · Hybrid", "description": "This lab's overarching objectives are to determine the extent that humans can switch between various tasks accurately and quickly from a cognitive psychology and neuroscience perspective.

As a first-year, I helped determine how attention is not completely localized or globalized while maintaining significant differences between repeated and switched tasks within each zone state. I continued this work in the proceeding two semesters by replicating the study's data collection with 30 online participants. 

As a second-year, I analyzed the online zone state data and statistically compared their quantitative and qualitative differences in attention to the in-person participants. Furthermore, I helped refine and provide statistical analysis for pilot participants of a behavioral, visual task (called the gradCPT task) associated with measuring attentional differences using binaural beats.

As a third-year, I designed a thesis project that combined the binaural beats' visual task and my auditory task to investigate if the same attentional fluctuations within subjects is replicable with multiple sensory networks. Additionally, I presented at the Annual Biomedical Research Conference for Minoritized Students (ABRCMS) on work seeking to replicate the brain regional activity of task engagement from suspenseful content to online instructional content."}, {"title": "NC A&T Summer Research Assistant", "company": "Newman Lab", "work_type": "Internship", "start_date": "May 2024", "end_date": "Jul 2024", "location": "North Carolina Agricultural and Technical University · On-site", "description": "Overall, the lab seeks to understand the mechanisms of redox kinase signaling from a cellular biology perspective.

My project investigates how equilibrium binding affects the affinity of protein-kinase A (PKA) towards CREBtide using a surface plasmon resonance machine. {"about": "✨ Welcome to the diary of a dreamer.

Upon self-teaching myself digital painting at fifteen, I got enthralled by how technology and art could intersect through design, which brought me to pursue an Honors Program degree in Computational Media (with People and Interaction Design concentrations) and a minor in Industrial Design at Georgia Tech.

I love wandering upon the realms of UI/UX design, graphic design, frontend development, and digital marketing. My designs range from goofy animation reels on YouTube to wireframes for a potential app - either way, I find true joy in crafting digital creations that draw smiles on people around me.

In my free time, I draw, vlog, play the ukulele, sing, write poems... and am a hopeful romantic.

{"about": "As a game designer, I create interesting systems and designs to bring the most out of a player’s time with a game. My expertise is in working with teams to develop a finished product that helps bring the most out of my client’s ideas. I am a jack of all trades that can fit well into most project settings and I’m very excited to begin my professional career in the video game industry.

𝐌𝐲 𝐏𝐚𝐬𝐬𝐢𝐨𝐧
I love stories. Ever since I was a child, I loved being able to explore unknown worlds, meet quirky characters, and enjoy new experiences. There is something special about diving into someone else’s story. Through this experience I learned what it means to ask, “Why?” 

Every person has a story that has brought them to where they are now. I love learning about their stories and telling them to others. I use this knowledge to its fullest when creating games that seek to highlight their stories.

{"about": "I am a fourth year student at the Georgia Institute of Technology, pursuing a Bachelor of Science in Aerospace Engineering. I'm currently enrolled in the BS/MS Aerospace Honors Program, where I am conducting guided aerospace research. My research focuses on developing a flow pattern manipulator device to create varying flow conditions present in different aerodynamic devices, allowing those devices to be tested in a controlled wind tunnel environment. This involves integrating static 3D-printed parts on an upstream linear slider and actuator, combined with a downstream pitot tube rake and actuator that creates a pressure map and detects irregular flow created by the manipulator device. In addition to my studies where I have maintained a 3.8+ GPA, I have also been a member of the Robonav Software Team where I helped develop an autonomous drone and rover to compete in the University Rover Competition. {"about": "My mission is to help over 1 million businesses realize the potential of entry level talent and help them hire the right ones for their organization.

Over the last 3 years, I've been working towards accomplishing this goal and built a business that connects companies to university talent for internships/full-time jobs.

Now, a little bit more about my journey...

For the first 25 years of my life I played the game of life - went to a good school growing up, then a great college, and then a kick-ass job at a Fortune 500 company when I graduated.

This game wasn't that much fun to me. It felt like I was rolling 1s and I wanted to be rolling 10s.

So, I decided to pivot from the scripted course and take the plunge into entrepreneurship. I started a company, Runway, which is a marketplace to hire vetted university students and fresh grads for part-time internships, full-time internships, and their first jobs out of school.

We've worked with nearly 300 different companies getting them highly motivated students to do work in business development, software development, and data analytics. We're totally bootstrapped and have only used the cash flows of the business to build it up.

Check us out at www.joinrunway.io!
If you are interested in hiring vetted entry-level talent my email is ford@joinrunway.io.

On Linkedin, I post about how YOU can elevate your career too so follow me if you want to start rolling 10s instead of being okay with rolling 1s.

Check me out on YouTube, Instagram, and X for more content like this:

YouTube: https://tapthe.link/7laQlkWJ8I

{"about": "I am currently a Senior at the Georgia Institute of Technology, pursuing a BS/MS in Computer Science with concentrations in Intelligence and Modeling/Simulation for my BS degree, and Computational Perception and Robotics for my MS degree. I am also minoring in Mathematics. My research interests include Artificial Intelligence, Modeling and Simulations, Computer Vision, and Robotics. Specifically, I am eager to explore the confluence of Machine Learning and Computer Vision to enable intelligent decision-making in robotic systems and to analyze their behaviors using computational modeling and simulation techniques. {"about": "Hello! 

I'm a third year undergraduate student pursuing a Bachelor of Science in Computer Science and a Bachelor of Science in Mathematics at the Georgia Institute of Technology with specializations in Systems Software, Computer Architecture, and Machine Learning.

With a strong foundation in C and C++ programming, I have work experience in developing efficient, real-time systems software for embedded platforms. Additionally, my coursework and personal projects have exposed me to RTL programming in Verilog and applying Python for machine learning using tools like NumPy, scikit-learn, and PyTorch.
